00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:03.000
Let's quickly introduce Quarto.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:09.000
Quarto is an open-source scientific and technical publishing system built on Pandoc.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:17.000
It's a project sponsored by Posit, taking what we've learned from creating our markdown with the goal of making it easier to create scientific documents.

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:22.000
You can write together narrative and code to produce beautiful and professional outputs.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:26.000
And if you haven't used it before, there are several benefits.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:32.000
Quarto offers a unified syntax for core features and maintains consistency across all formats.

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:38.000
Features like tab sets and code folding and cross-referencing all function in the same way.

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:47.000
Additionally, Quarto provides a universal theming system based on SAS for all HTML output, using core variables defined by BSLib.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:54.000
Quarto can be called from the terminal or the command line and is completely independent of computational systems.

00:03:54.000 --> 00:04:00.000
While Quarto supports NIDAR, the engine behind our markdown, it can also support other systems.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:05.000
And ultimately, the goal is to create dynamic outputs that are reproducible and easy to create.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:14.000
Quarto enables single-source publishing, where different output formats like websites, presentations, and more are created from a single source.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:16.000
Here's how Quarto works in the backend.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:18.000
An engine is the tool that runs code.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:25.000
This is the basic structure that creates documents from the source, the Quarto markdown file or the QMD file.

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:35.000
When we render a Quarto document first, the engine executes all of the code chunks and generates an intermediary markdown file that includes both the code and the code output.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:39.000
Then that markdown file is processed by Pandoc to create the finished document.

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:44.000
Today, we'll be using the Jupyter engine since we are creating a dashboard of Python.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:51.000
But all the same principles apply to the NIDAR engine for R because Quarto is inherently multi-engine.

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:55.000
And here is an example Quarto document.

00:04:55.000 --> 00:05:02.000
At the top in the YAML header, we specify the format and the engine we're using, in this case, Jupyter.

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:11.000
Then within the document itself, we have text and executable code here in a Python chunk.

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:17.000
Running or rendering this document on the left gives us the document or the output on the right.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:25.000
Here's another Quarto document where instead of format HTML, we have format reveal.js.

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:36.000
And changing just the format without changing the actual content of the document gives us another output but with the same information, the presentation on the right.

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:40.000
Now let's talk about Quarto dashboards.

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:49.000
Quarto dashboards is an exciting new feature that allows you to create static and interactive dashboards using Python, R, Julia, and Observable.

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:56.000
Below are some excellent examples from my colleagues, which you can see in the Quarto dashboard gallery link below.

00:05:56.000 --> 00:06:07.000
Released in Quarto 1.4, users can develop beautiful dashboards with a diverse range of components such as Plotly, Leaflet, Tables, Text, and more.

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:13.000
These dashboards offer extensive customization options, allowing you to define layouts.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:17.000
You can author content in your preferred notebook editor.

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:22.000
And you can choose between static or interactive formats based on your needs and preferences.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:24.000
Here's an example.

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:33.000
This Python dashboard contained on a single page uses interactive Plotly visualizations to examine development indicators within the Gap Manager dataset.

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:37.000
It features two rows, with the second row divided into two columns.

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:42.000
And as mentioned earlier, what we need to do is define the format as dashboard.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:45.000
Let me walk you through some of the key features.

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:55.000
Dashboards can include navigation bars, organized rows and columns, tab sets, cards, other content, and sidebars and toolbars for functionality.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:07:01.000
Just so you know, we are going to be talking about this in a very high level way.

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:09.000
If you're watching this video before August 12th, we are hosting a Quarto dashboards workshop at PositConf 2024.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:11.000
We'd love to see you there.

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:21.000
All dashboards feature a top-level navigation bar, which offers a title, and optionally, a logo and author information.

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:29.000
For dashboards with multiple pages, each page is linked within the navigation bar, as you can see here.

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:35.000
Within a page, dashboard components are organized using alternating sets of rows and columns.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:40.000
These rows and columns are defined by markdown headings and computational cells.

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:47.000
For instance, here's a layout with two rows, where the second row is divided into two columns.

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:51.000
By default, dashboard pages are laid out first by row, then column.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:58.000
However, you can change this by specifying the orientation columns document option.

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:04.000
Tab sets are a useful tool for incorporating multiple perspectives of data or showcasing secondary content.

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:09.000
You can create tab sets by applying the tab set class to a row or column.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:15.000
For instance, here's a layout where the bottom row is presented as a pair of tabs.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:18.000
Sidebars are a great place to group inputs for dashboards.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:23.000
To include a sidebar, add the sidebar class to a level 2 heading.

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:28.000
Cards serve as the basic building blocks for displaying content within dashboards.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:33.000
They are automatically generated for cells and markdown content within rows and columns.

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:41.000
For instance, here, each cell would translate into a separate card within the dashboard layout.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:48.000
And here's an example of a card and the corresponding output.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:54.000
Dashboards are essentially collections of components designed to facilitate navigation and present data.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:58.000
Here there are various methods that you can use in a Cordo dashboard.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:05.000
Plots represent the most common form of content, supporting both interactive JavaScript-based plots like Altair and Plotly,

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:12.000
as well as standard raster-based plots like Matplotlib and ggplot2.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:17.000
Data tables can be incorporated into dashboards as a straightforward tabular display

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:23.000
or as an interactive widget with sorting and filtering capabilities.

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:30.000
Value boxes offer prominent means of showcasing simple values within a dashboard.

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:34.000
And while dashboards typically feature plots and tables within cards,

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:41.000
you can also include arbitrary markdown content anywhere within a dashboard layout.

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:49.000
And here are some examples of plots, value boxes, tables, and some markdown content.

